#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:94
#, no-c-format
msgid "Sparse Image Files and Disk Space"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:96
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If the host’s physical disk reaches a state where it has no available space, "
"a virtual machine using a virtual disk based on a sparse image file cannot "
"write to its disk. Consequently, it reports I/O errors."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:102
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If this situation occurs, you should free up available space on the physical "
"disk, remount the virtual machine’s file system, and set the file system "
"back to read-write."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:109
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To check the actual disk requirements of a sparse image file, use the "
"command <command>du -h &lt;image file&gt;</command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:114
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To increase the available space of a sparse image file, first increase the "
"file size and then the file system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:120
#, no-c-format
msgid "Back Up Before Resizing"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:121
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Touching the sizes of partitions or sparse files always bears the risk of "
"data failure. Do not work without a backup."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:127
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The resizing of the image file can be done online, while the &vmguest; is "
"running. Increase the size of a sparse image file with:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:132
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"dd if=/dev/zero of=&lt;image file&gt; count=0 bs=1M seek=&lt;new size in "
"MB&gt;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:134
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, to increase the file <filename>/var/lib/xen/images/sles/disk0</"
"filename> to a size of 16GB, use the command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:140
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"dd if=/dev/zero of=/var/lib/xen/images/sles/disk0 count=0 bs=1M seek=16000"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:143
#, no-c-format
msgid "Increasing Non-Sparse Images"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:144
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It is also possible to increase the image files of devices that are not "
"sparse files. However, you must know exactly where the previous image ends. "
"Use the seek parameter to point to the end of the image file and use a "
"command similar to the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:150
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"dd if=/dev/zero of=/var/lib/xen/images/sles/disk0 seek=8000 bs=1M count=2000"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:153
#, no-c-format
msgid "Be sure to use the right seek, else data loss may happen."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:157
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If the &vmguest; is running during the resize operation, also resize the "
"loop device that provides the image file to the &vmguest;. First detect the "
"correct loop device with the command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:163
#, no-c-format
msgid "losetup -j /var/lib/xen/images/sles/disk0"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:165
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Then resize the loop device, for example <filename>/dev/loop0</filename>, "
"with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:170
#, no-c-format
msgid "losetup -c /dev/loop0"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:172
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Finally check the size of the block device inside the guest system with the "
"command <command>fdisk -l /dev/xvdb</command>. The device name depends on "
"the actually increased device."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:178
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The resizing of the file system inside the sparse file involves tools that "
"are depending on the actual file system. <phrase os=\"sles\">This is "
"described in detail in the <xref linkend=\"stor_admin\"/>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:185
#, no-c-format
msgid "Migrating &xen; &vmguest; Systems"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:187
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"With &xen; it is possible to migrate a &vmguest; system from one &vmhost; to "
"another with almost no service interruption. This could be used for example "
"to move a busy &vmguest; to a &vmhost; that has stronger hardware or is not "
"yet loaded. Or, if a service of a &vmhost; is required, all &vmguest; "
"systems running on this machine can be migrated to other machines to avoid "
"interruption of service. These are only two examples&mdash;many more reasons "
"may apply to your personal situation."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:198
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Before starting, some preliminary considerations regarding the &vmhost; "
"should be taken into account:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:205
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"All &vmhost; systems should use a similar CPU. The frequency is not so "
"important, but they should be using the same CPU family. To get more "
"information about the used CPU, see <command>cat /proc/cpuinfo</command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:213
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"All resources that are used by a specific guest system must be available on "
"all involved &vmhost; systems&mdash;for example all used block devices must "
"exist on both &vmhost; systems."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:220
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If the hosts included in the migration process run in different subnets, "
"make sure that either DHCP relay is available to the guests, or for guests "
"with static network configuration, set up the network manually."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:227
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Using special features like <literal>&pciback;</literal> may be problematic. "
"Do not implement these when deploying for an environment that should migrate "
"&vmguest; systems between different &vmhost; systems."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:235
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For fast migrations, a fast network is mandatory. If possible, use GB "
"Ethernet and fast switches. Deploying VLAN might also help avoid collisions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:244
#, no-c-format
msgid "Preparing Block Devices for Migrations"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:245
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The block devices needed by the &vmguest; system must be available on all "
"involved &vmhost; systems. This is done by implementing some kind of shared "
"storage that serves as container for the root file system of the migrated "
"&vmguest; system. Common possibilities include:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:253
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>iSCSI</literal> can be set up to give access to the same block "
"devices from different systems at the same time. <phrase os=\"sles\">For "
"more information about iSCSI, see <xref linkend=\"cha.iscsi\"/>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:260
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>NFS</literal> is a widely used root file system that can easily be "
"accessed from different locations. For more information, see <xref linkend="
"\"cha.nfs\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:267
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>DRBD</literal> can be used if only two &vmhost; systems are "
"involved. This gives some extra data security, because the used data is "
"mirrored over the network. <phrase os=\"sles;sled\">For more information, "
"see the <citetitle>SUSE Linux Enterprise High Availability Extension "
"&productnumber;</citetitle> documentation at <link xlink:href=\"http://www."
"suse.com/doc/\"></link></phrase>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:277
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>SCSI</literal> can also be used if the available hardware permits "
"shared access to the same disks."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:283
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>NPIV</literal> is a special mode to use Fibre channel disks. "
"However, in this case all migration hosts must be attached to the same Fibre "
"channel switch. For more information about NPIV, see <xref linkend=\"sec.xen."
"config.disk\"/>. Commonly, this works if the Fibre channel environment "
"supports 4 Gbit or faster connections."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:295
#, no-c-format
msgid "Migrating &vmguest; Systems"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:296
#, no-c-format
msgid "The actual migration of the &vmguest; system is done with the command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:300
#, no-c-format
msgid "xl migrate &lt;domain_name&gt; &lt;host&gt;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:301
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The speed of the migration depends on how fast the memory print can be saved "
"to disk, sent to the new &vmhost; and loaded there. This means that small "
"&vmguest; systems can be migrated faster than big systems with a lot of "
"memory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:310
#, no-c-format
msgid "Monitoring &xen;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:312
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For a regular operation of many virtual guests, having a possibility to "
"check the sanity of all the different &vmguest; systems is indispensable. "
"&xen; offers several tools besides the system tools to gather information "
"about the system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:320
#, no-c-format
msgid "Monitoring the &vmhost;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:321
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Basic monitoring of the &vmhost; (I/O and CPU) is available via the &vmm;. "
"Refer to <xref linkend=\"cha.libvirt.admin.monitor.virt-manager\"/> for "
"details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:329
#, no-c-format
msgid "Monitor &xen; with <command>xentop</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:330
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The preferred terminal application to gather information about &xen; virtual "
"environment is <command>xentop</command>. Unfortunately, this tool needs a "
"rather broad terminal, else it inserts line breaks into the display."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:336
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<command>xentop</command> has several command keys that can give you more "
"information about the system that is monitored. Some of the more important "
"are:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: xen_administrating.xml:343
#, no-c-format
msgid "<term>D</term>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:345
#, no-c-format
msgid "Change the delay between the refreshes of the screen."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: xen_administrating.xml:351
#, no-c-format
msgid "<term>N</term>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:353
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Also display network statistics. Note, that only standard configurations "
"will be displayed. If you use a special configuration like a routed network, "
"no network will be displayed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: xen_administrating.xml:361
#, no-c-format
msgid "<term>B</term>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:363
#, no-c-format
msgid "Display the respective block devices and their cumulated usage count."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:369
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more information about <command>xentop</command> see the manual page "
"<command>man 1 xentop</command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:376
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"libvirt offers the hypervisor-agnostic tool <command>virt-top</command>, "
"which is recommended for monitoring &vmguest;s. See <xref linkend=\"cha."
"libvirt.admin.monitor.virt-top\"/> for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:386
#, no-c-format
msgid "Additional Tools"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:387
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"There are many system tools that also help monitoring or debugging a running "
"&sle; system. Many of these are covered in the official &sle; documentation. "
"Especially useful for monitoring a virtualization environment are the "
"following tools:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: xen_administrating.xml:395
#, no-c-format
msgid "<term>ip</term>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:397
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The command line utility <command>ip</command> may be used to monitor "
"arbitrary network interfaces. This is especially useful if you have set up a "
"network that is routed or applied a masqueraded network. To monitor a "
"network interface with the name <literal>&xenguest;.0</literal>, run the "
"following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:404
#, no-c-format
msgid "watch ip -s link show &xenguest;.0"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: xen_administrating.xml:408
#, no-c-format
msgid "brctl"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:410
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In a standard setup, all the &xen; &vmguest; systems are attached to a "
"virtual network bridge. <command>brctl</command> allows you to determine the "
"connection between the bridge and the virtual network adapter in the "
"&vmguest; system. For example, the output of <command>brctl show</command> "
"may look like the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:417
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"bridge name     bridge id               STP enabled     interfaces\n"
"br0             8000.000476f060cc       no              eth0\n"
"                                                        vif1.0\n"
"br1             8000.00001cb5a9e7       no              vlan22"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:418
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This shows that there are two virtual bridges defined on the system. One is "
"connected to the physical Ethernet device <literal>eth0</literal>, the other "
"one is connected to a VLAN interface <literal>vlan22</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:424
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"There is only one guest interface active in this setup, <literal>vif1.0</"
"literal>. This means that the guest with ID 1 has an Ethernet interface "
"<literal>eth0</literal> assigned, that is connected to <literal>br0</"
"literal> in the &vmhost;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: xen_administrating.xml:433
#, no-c-format
msgid "iptables-save"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:435
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Especially when using masquerade networks, or if several Ethernet interfaces "
"are set up together with a firewall setup, it may be helpful to check the "
"current firewall rules."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:440
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The command <command>iptables</command> may be used to check all the "
"different firewall settings. To list all the rules of a chain, or even of "
"the complete setup, you may use the commands <command>iptables-save</"
"command> or <command>iptables -S</command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: xen_administrating.xml:452
#, no-c-format
msgid "Providing Host Information for &vmguest; Systems"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:454
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In a standard &xen; environment, the &vmguest; systems have only very "
"limited information about the &vmhost; system they are running on. If a "
"guest should know more about the &vmhost; it runs on, <systemitem>vhostmd</"
"systemitem> can provide more information to selected guests. To set up your "
"system to run <systemitem>vhostmd</systemitem>, proceed as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:465
#, no-c-format
msgid "Install the package vhostmd on the &vmhost;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:470
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To add or remove <literal>metric</literal> sections from the configuration, "
"edit the file <filename>/etc/vhostmd/vhostmd.conf</filename>. However, the "
"default works well."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:478
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Check the validity of the <filename>vhostmd.conf</filename> configuration "
"file with the command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:482
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"cd /etc/vhostmd\n"
"xmllint --postvalid --noout vhostmd.conf"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:485
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Start the vhostmd daemon with the command <command>sudo systemctl start "
"vhostmd</command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:489
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If vhostmd should be started automatically during start-up of the system, "
"run the command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:493
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo systemctl enable vhostmd"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:496
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Attach the image file <filename>/dev/shm/vhostmd0</filename> to the "
"&vmguest; system named &xenguest; with the command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: xen_administrating.xml:500
#, no-c-format
msgid "xl block-attach opensuse /dev/shm/vhostmd0,,xvdb,ro"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:503
#, no-c-format
msgid "Log on the &vmguest; system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:508
#, no-c-format
msgid "Install the client package <systemitem>vm-dump-metrics</systemitem>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:513
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Run the command <command>vm-dump-metrics</command>. To save the result to a "
"file, use the option <systemitem>-d &lt;filename&gt;</systemitem>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:520
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The result of the <systemitem>vm-dump-metrics</systemitem> is an XML output. "
"The respective metric entries follow the DTD <filename>/etc/vhostmd/metric."
"dtd</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: xen_administrating.xml:526
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more information, see the manual pages <command>man 8 vhostmd</command> "
"and <filename>/usr/share/doc/vhostmd/README</filename> on the &vmhost; "
"system. On the guest, see the manual page <command>man 1 vm-dump-metrics</"
"command>."
msgstr ""
